WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.320
Hi, my name is David Alja. I'm a member of the Solutions Engineering team at Posit and

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:21.000
the world's worst Kelly O'Brien impersonator. And with that said, let's talk about Connect.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:28.240
So I like to think about deploying things to Connect as a magic trick. Not magic. In

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:34.520
this house, we respect the laws of physics and computers, large language models notwithstanding,

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:41.959
are deterministic. But as a magic trick in the taxonomy proposed by a particular Christopher

00:00:41.959 --> 00:00:50.240
Nolan movie. A trick comes in three phases. The first is the pledge. I show you something

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:57.040
you've seen before. I encourage you to inspect it. I tell you that it's ordinary. It's a

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:08.279
shiny app that runs at extraordinary zoom on your laptop. Or alternatively, it's a shiny

00:01:08.279 --> 00:01:18.919
app built in Python, which I guess is a little bit more novel, that runs again on your laptop.

00:01:18.919 --> 00:01:23.040
I encourage you to look at the shiny app. If it was cooler in here, I would remove my

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:27.760
jacket. Or warmer in here, I would remove my jacket. There's nothing up my sleeves.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:36.480
The second phase of the trick is called the turn. In the turn, you begin to suspect that

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:46.120
something about this is not ordinary. And so that's the wrong app. Hooray for command

00:01:46.120 --> 00:02:02.080
history. But I'm going to deploy the shiny app. Or I could jump over to the IDE and publish

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:10.559
this application. And so I'm showing you now, you know, a bunch of logs. Something is clearly

00:02:10.559 --> 00:02:18.479
happening. It's not clear what. But a bunch of logs does not really make a magic trick.

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:25.399
I can't just make the app disappear. It has to go somewhere else. And so that's where

00:02:25.399 --> 00:02:32.440
we get to the third phase of the trick. The hardest part. Where I make the app reappear

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:40.960
on Kinect. And we call that part the prestige. It's a great movie. But in this case, the

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:53.080
trick is not actually that the app is running on Kinect. The trick, and I'm typing super

00:02:53.080 --> 00:03:02.520
fast right now, is that the app is running in a container. And so now, like any magician,

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:06.839
what I will do is I'm going to take you behind the trick and then we'll talk a little bit

00:03:06.839 --> 00:03:11.679
about whether this is a thing you should try at home.

00:03:11.679 --> 00:03:18.119
So to begin, let's start by talking about Kinect. What is Kinect? Kinect, I think, I

00:03:18.639 --> 00:03:23.639
like to try to define things by what they do. And what Kinect does is it drives down

00:03:23.639 --> 00:03:28.000
the cost of application publishing. I think people at this conference are probably pretty

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.919
used to the idea that data scientists are people who in the course of doing their work

00:03:32.919 --> 00:03:38.279
builds web applications. But that's not a typical view that most people hold about one

00:03:38.279 --> 00:03:44.199
of the things that data science is. And so part of what Kinect does is it makes it easy

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:49.679
for data scientists to get work off their machines by reducing the demands on what it

00:03:49.679 --> 00:03:54.919
asks them for when they're trying to publish something. So Kinect's deployments do lots

00:03:54.919 --> 00:04:00.320
of work to inspect your local environment, gather up some information about what you

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:05.119
have there, and then send that to the server where Kinect reconstructs the environment

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:12.520
for you. And Kinect servers, and I have one of those architecture diagrams that James

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:18.760
pulled up before, a single Kinect server can run multiple versions of R, multiple versions

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:24.079
of Python, multiple versions of Quarto. It can handle conflicting versions of packages

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:30.399
for each of those runtimes. And it deploys the applications in an isolated and atomic

00:04:30.399 --> 00:04:34.679
way. So it makes it, again, it's trivial to publish a new thing. If you break it, you

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:40.760
just publish again. You roll forward, you iterate, you make progress. And for most,

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:49.320
many workflows, that's good enough. There are, however, circumstances where more

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:56.600
complexity is required. That might be because you're working with packages that are for

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:02.779
some reason difficult to install. They might have complicated dependencies that are difficult

00:05:02.779 --> 00:05:07.640
for something running at the application layer to reconstruct. There might be conflicting

00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:13.880
package dependencies. You might have data that's stored in, you might have data that's

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:18.559
stored somewhere that demands something else about the way you access that data. So the

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:25.559
Linux file system is no longer enough. And so for all of those reasons, we've put a lot

00:05:25.559 --> 00:05:35.519
of work into making it possible to run Kinect in Kubernetes. We've decoupled where Kinect

00:05:35.519 --> 00:05:42.160
runs and where applications run. Applications sit in their own container context, and Kinect

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:47.799
is responsible for spawning them and managing some other things. And we call this mode off-host

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:53.279
execution. And so what I want to do now is I want to show you around some of the Kinect

00:05:53.279 --> 00:05:57.679
interfaces that reflect this change so that you can understand what kinds of things are

00:05:57.679 --> 00:06:03.720
possible when Kinect is running in this mode. So I'll jump back to our shiny application

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:08.920
here. And if you look at the right side, you'll see that below the settings where we

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:15.200
can control the access to the application or the sub-path we serve it on, we have some

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:20.399
additional configuration settings. And so in addition to controlling the, for example,

00:06:20.399 --> 00:06:27.760
the user executing the content, we might also provide a specific Kubernetes service account,

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:32.519
which would have permissions to access particular data sources in a way that isn't going to

00:06:32.519 --> 00:06:36.480
sort of correspond to how we do that in the Linux file system. And that's going to make

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:45.959
it easier to provide that fine-grained permission. The other new sort of option you're seeing

00:06:45.959 --> 00:06:53.440
here is the ability to configure execution environments on a per-deployment basis. And

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:58.559
so what you're seeing here is I pushed a container to the GitHub container registry that just

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:05.480
has a version of Python in it, but I can change that environment to be something more complicated.

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:10.160
It might be the case that, for example, I have an image that has R and Python in it.

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:14.559
And if I'm thinking about making changes to my application, I can select a different image

00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:20.359
for subsequent execution. And I can also select that as a default environment image. If I

00:07:20.359 --> 00:07:25.119
come back to the Kinect home page, you'll see there's an additional tab that explains

00:07:25.119 --> 00:07:31.720
the execution environments that are available. And so in addition to the default images that

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:39.160
Kinect ships with in the Helm chart I used to provision this instance, I've added this

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:47.679
Python 3.10 image and also an image that has a version of Quarto 1.4 in it. I am extremely

00:07:47.679 --> 00:07:52.880
excited about Quarto 1.4. And if you want to understand why, you should go to Carlos

00:07:52.880 --> 00:08:01.880
Scheidegger's talk. But that's not all, right? So in addition to wanting to, say, constrain

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:07.720
the environment that we're constructing as Kinect is being built, one of the other things

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:13.679
we might need is the ability to control the resources that are being consumed by the application

00:08:13.679 --> 00:08:21.200
while it runs. And so in addition to memory limits, which you can apply now in both local

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:27.480
and off-host execution mode, you can also apply CPU limits. This means that if you have

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:31.839
applications that have a way of spinning out, taking down servers, and forcing you to buy

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:36.880
people beers, you can put a little bit more guardrails around that in a way that's going

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:42.760
to make your application safer to use. And then the last thing, and this is one of the

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:49.200
newest pieces of functionality that we've introduced to Kinect, is the ability to bypass

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:53.960
certain elements of environment reconstruction. You can see here on both the R environment

00:08:53.960 --> 00:09:00.200
and Python environment management, we have the option to select a setting which gives

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:06.479
us control over who has responsibility for environment construction. So I pushed a container

00:09:06.479 --> 00:09:12.200
that has just a Python image in it, and so I allowed Kinect to build the content in my

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:17.400
container. It's also the case that I could construct an environment that has all the

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:23.840
dependencies that my application requires, and then push that container to Kinect, and

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:29.239
Kinect doesn't have to actually do that environment restoration step. And so that's giving you,

00:09:29.239 --> 00:09:37.520
again, more fine-grained control over what exactly is executing and where. So that's,

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:43.919
I think, a quick overview of some of the things that we've changed about Kinect to make it

00:09:43.919 --> 00:09:48.559
a better citizen in Kubernetes. And I think I'll stop there and take any questions that

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:49.559
anyone has.

00:09:49.559 --> 00:10:04.080
Thank you, David. The first question I have here reads, can we also run Kinect workloads

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:08.239
in the Slurm cluster in the future to match Workbench?

00:10:08.239 --> 00:10:13.719
So that's an excellent question. One thing I would say on the question of matching Workbench

00:10:13.719 --> 00:10:18.799
is that if you're running Workbench in an off-house execution mode, there's some documentation

00:10:18.799 --> 00:10:22.799
we're polishing on this now, but one of the things people often want to do is take the

00:10:22.799 --> 00:10:26.840
container image they've defined for Workbench and then pull that over to Kinect and use

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:31.280
it. It's not necessarily the fastest way to do that, but it gives you a very clear idea

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:36.760
about what's executing here and here. And so that is definitely something you can do.

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:44.559
Actually, we are still thinking about other venues for this distributed execution model.

00:10:44.559 --> 00:10:46.760
Let's chat later about your interest in Slurm.

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:53.359
Thank you. All right. The next one says, is there a way to speed up the launch of content

00:10:53.359 --> 00:10:59.239
of pods when they're open? Takes a few seconds longer than I'd like.

00:10:59.239 --> 00:11:09.760
Some of that will, I think, yeah, I believe that an option where more of the, where if

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:14.880
you have, essentially if you bake the content into the image, then you will bypass some

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:20.000
of the steps that increase the startup time in off-host execution mode. So that might

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:26.200
be one way to think about increasing the startup time if you're concerned about that.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:36.679
Thank you. All right. So the next one says, sorry, they're moving around here. On a single

00:11:36.679 --> 00:11:44.960
server instance, we'd normally patch the server, for example, apt-get, and the content would

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:50.919
not be affected. Can I patch execution images without worry?

00:11:50.919 --> 00:11:59.919
Can you patch execution images? I, that's an interesting, I suppose you could patch

00:11:59.919 --> 00:12:02.239
the image, but I wouldn't. I guess rebuild the image?

00:12:02.239 --> 00:12:05.679
Yeah, I would just build a new, I would build, I would think about that as an opportunity

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:12.200
to build and publish a new image. Yeah. Makes sense. Yep. All right. So do you

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:18.280
find that some of your clients want more control of the resources that connect apps or APIs

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:24.479
consumed, similarly of how our studio on SageMaker works?

00:12:24.479 --> 00:12:31.960
So the, I think some of the settings that I showed on the, in the runtime panel give

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:37.440
you a little bit more control over the maximum CPU and memory that applications will consume.

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:42.400
So that's one limit you can impose. The lifecycle is a bit different to SageMaker because you're

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:49.479
starting each, each SageMaker instance is essentially its own, its own EC2 instance,

00:12:49.479 --> 00:12:55.239
whereas these are typically pods that are running on a, on a node. And so I think it's

00:12:55.239 --> 00:12:59.440
slightly different, but you get to control things in either way.

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:06.799
Okay. Let's see here. Make sure we're on time here. I think so. So what is handling the

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:12.960
workload resources for say a fractional CPU course or memory? Is Connect communicating

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:18.200
with the Kubernetes engine or changing node pool specs?

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:25.119
So Connect embeds the service. If you've heard people talk about the launcher service, it's

00:13:25.119 --> 00:13:28.440
responsible for communicating with the Kubernetes API.

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:38.640
Makes sense. All right. Next one says, is there a case where one can use Kubernetes

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:44.799
and open a Shiny server perhaps for local pod-based testing without ingress or egress

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:51.200
consequences on Connect in a cloud?

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:53.400
I'm trying to parse that one too.

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:54.400
Could you one more?

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:58.400
So let's do it again. All right. Let's try it again. Let's see.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:04.400
Is there a case where one can use Kubernetes and the open Shiny server perhaps for local

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:09.679
pod-based testing without ingress and egress consequences on Connect in a cloud?

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:10.679
I see.

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:15.080
So I guess if you want to test that, yeah.

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:21.359
You certainly could. I think there's a, it's kind of a philosophy of testing question.

00:14:21.359 --> 00:14:27.599
And at that point, I'm not sure what you would be testing.

