00:15:47.679 --> 00:15:52.679
So when you deploy an app to an environment, the packages the app uses are baked into the

00:15:52.679 --> 00:15:57.679
container image and not a library directory mounted on a shared disk?

00:15:57.679 --> 00:16:07.679
No. So the, and I elided this because of the magic metaphor, but the environment restoration

00:16:07.679 --> 00:16:15.679
is happening on the NFS persistent volume that's attached to the cluster. And so the

00:16:15.679 --> 00:16:22.679
concept that you'll have seen in local execution modes of Connect about the cache, that mechanism

00:16:22.679 --> 00:16:32.679
is still preserved. So the content is ultimately associated with a runtime cache that you can

00:16:32.679 --> 00:16:36.679
sort of do surgery on as needed.

00:16:36.679 --> 00:16:41.679
So how challenging will it be to deploy from Workbench instance running on Kubernetes to

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:45.679
a Connect app deployed on Kubernetes?

00:16:45.679 --> 00:16:51.679
That's going to depend a lot on what, it's going to depend a lot on the environment, right?

00:16:51.679 --> 00:16:56.679
An application that doesn't have any complicated dependencies like the ones I deployed, you

00:16:56.679 --> 00:17:02.679
can see they were running locally on my laptop. I deployed them into a cluster, into a container.

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:07.680
I didn't really have to do anything to make that happen. If you have more complicated dependencies

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:13.680
then you might need to be a little bit more thoughtful about how you describe your desired

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:19.680
deployment. Both the RSConnect package and the Python command line interface provide

00:17:19.680 --> 00:17:24.680
ways for you to select a specific image to execute the content as long as that image

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:30.680
is known to the server. And so you do get a lot of flexibility there about either deciding

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:35.680
to let Connect pick an image for you or specifying one if that's the desired outcome.

